IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Detailed Crash Investigation Report (For review by the MSPCrash Team) Section I. - Introduction: On March 26, 2023, at approximately 0235 hours, a motor vehicle collision involving a pedestrian was reported to the Maryland State Police Rockville Barrack. The reported location was on the westbound side of the Capital Beltway (I-495), in the area of New Hampshire Avenue (MD Rt. 650), Silver Spring, Montgomery County, MD. Upon the arrival of Maryland State Police Troopers, they observed a white passenger vehicle on the right shoulder of the westbound side of I-495, just past exit for northbound New Hampshire Avenue, Montgomery County, Maryland; however initially were unable to locate the involved pedestrian. Montgomery County Fire and Rescue responded and were able to locate the struck pedestrian on the westbound side of I-495, west of Riggs Road on the left shoulder. Paramedics were called to the scene, and the pedestrian stuck was pronounced deceased on scene. Due to the nature of the collision, I Trooper Ryan Stewart #7590, a Collision Reconstructionist assigned to the Maryland State Police College Park Barrack, was contacted to respond to the collision scene to assume the investigation and I responded at 0250 hours. Upon my arrival at 0316 hours, I observed the scene was contained by Maryland State Police Troopers, Montgomery County Police, and Montgomery County Fire and Rescue. The scope of this investigation will address various elements that caused and/or contributed to the collision events. This investigations conclusions were accomplished by either direct investigative actions or through the review of finding from other investigative sources. Section II. - Scene Description: (The following descriptions are based on the area where the collision occurred.) Primary Roadway: Outer Loop Capital Beltway west of Riggs Rd. overpass. The Capital Beltway in the area of the collision was a 6 lane divided highway, lanes indicated by broken white lane lines. There was a full left shoulder, indicated by a solid yellow lane line, which was affixed with a guardrail that lead to a concrete barrier. In the area of the crash, the right shoulder tapers to no shoulder, indicated by a solid white fog line, with a concrete barrier. The posted speed limit on the Capital Beltway was 55 miles-per-hour. At the time of the collision, the lighting condition was dark with no streetlights. The roadway was constructed of asphalt and was free of any defects that would have contributed to the cause of the collision. Secondary Roadway (if applicable): No secondary roadways were analyzed as part of this collision investigation. Environmental Conditions: Overcast / Light Fog approximately 52 Degrees Fahrenheit, calm winds and high humidity. The astronomy on March 26, 2023, was waxing (growing) crescent moon. The overcast conditions may have dimmed any moonlight reflectivity which may have illuminated the pedestrian. Section III. - Scene Evidence: As I was arriving on the scene I observed Montgomery County Police had all lanes of the westbound side of I-495 shut down just west of the I-95 interchange. While approaching the scene, I observed Montgomery County Fire and Rescue to still be on scene with a piece of fire apparatus parked at an angle across lanes one and two as well as multiple police units consisting of Montgomery County Police and Maryland State Police. I observed there to be two shoes in the roadway that were white and black. One shoe was in lane 1 and the other in lane 2. I made contact with Detective Sergeant (D/Sgt.) Heath, Assistant Commander of the College Park Barrack, who was on scene, at which time he advised it was a single vehicle and single pedestrian involved in the crash. D/Sgt. Heath further advised the Honda Accord was stopped further west on I-495 on the right shoulder and Trooper (Tpr.) Webb and Trooper First Class (TFC) Forsyth were with the occupants and the Honda Accord. My attention was then directed to the left shoulder where the Pedestrian, later identified as Sebastian Guzman-Vasquez (H/M 5/15/97), was laying at his final rest position in front of the fire apparatus. After gathering a brief overview of the scene I responded to the location of the vehicle, described as a white 2013 Honda Accord displaying MD Registration 1DX8600. V1 was stopped on the right shoulder and I observed it to have damage consistent with striking a pedestrian on the front drivers side of the vehicle including front bumper, headlight, hood, and windshield. I also observed there to be what appeared to be blood, brain matter, and other bodily fluid concentrated on the roof of the vehicle but also throughout the interior of the vehicle. I returned to the area of impact to continue the investigation. While observing the scene D/Sgt. Heath, I observed a gray sweatshirt in the trees/brush in the median off of the left shoulder. As I closer inspected the gray sweatshirt, I observed it had what appeared to be bodily fluid on it, as well as rips and tears. It appeared as if during the collision the clothing was thrown from Guzman-Vasquez possession/body. After documenting its location and condition, the sweatshirt was removed and a black smartphone device was located in the pocket. At this time, the identity of Guzman-Vasquez was unknown and no identification was able to be located on his person or in the area of the collision. D/Sgt. Heath contacted Emergency Operations Center (EOC) and obtained the phone number for the recovered cellular phone as (301) 835-3720. As the investigation continued, I marked and documented the locations of what I determined to be the area of impact, left shoe, right shoe and other roadway evidence. I observed the first trace of roadway evidence was in lane two, which was determined to have been the area of impact, and consisted of what appeared to be blood and bodily fluids. The evidence on the roadway, as well as debris field projected westward and the furthest east point with visible evidence was marked and measured from that point. Based off of scene evidence the area of impact is believed to be in the left half of lane 2 approximately 1/10 of a mile west of Riggs Rd. overpass. The following measurements were obtained on scene and are approximate measurements to the nearest inch. Area of Impact (AOI) will be used to distinguish where measurements were taken from using the solid yellow line parallel to AOI as the starting point to parallel with each piece of evidence. AOI - Left shoe (Left edge of Lane 1 with toe of shoe on solid yellow line) = 235 AOI - Gray Sweatshirt (median, over guardrail in bush branches) = 424 AOI - Right shoe (Right half of Lane 2) = 5911 AOI - Beginning of blood trail (Beginning in middle of Lane 1) = 976 AOI - P1 final rest position (Left edge of left shoulder) = 2089 Start of blood trail - P1 final rest position = 11111 Robert Tobin, the Forensic Investigator from the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner (OCME) responded to conduct their investigation. Tobin requested transport for Guzman-Vasquez to the OCME who responded and took possession of Guzman-Vasquez and transported him to the OCME located in Baltimore, Maryland so an autopsy could be conducted. After clearing the scene and reopening all lanes of the westbound side of the Capital Beltway, I returned to the College Park Barrack and completed necessary paperwork. Section IV. - Vehicle(s) Involved: Vehicle #1: Year / Make / Model: 2013 Honda Accord VIN: 1HGCR2F84DA202756 Registration:1DX8600/Maryland Registered Owner :Brandi Michelle Miller B/F DOB: 12/30/1993 901 Kings Valley Dr. Bowie, MD 20721 base64," style="height:131px; margin:5px 10px; width:175px" /> Section V. - Person(s) Involved: Operator #1: Name / DOB: Brandi Michelle Miller / DOB: 12/30/1993 License Number / State: M-460-098-603-995/Maryland Address: 901 Kings Valley Dr. Bowie, MD 20721 Phone Number: (301) 996-2071 Injured Status: Not Injured Impairment:Odor of an alcoholic beverage detected by Tpr. Webb. Miller performed the battery of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) Standardized Field Sobriety Test (SFST) and completed satisfactorily and did not display clues of impairment. Statement:Driving in the fast lane, while driving a male who was walking in the street on a four lane highway while on the phone came out of nowhere Passenger #1: Name / DOB:Ya Meshiadevoil Zsannique Rich /DOB: 11/08/1992 License Number / State:MD10273622054 / Maryland Address:12981 Middlebrook Rd. Apt. A Germantown, MD 20874 Phone Number:(240) 440-4191 Injured Status:Not Injured Impairment:Had been drinking Statement:I YaMeshiadevoil Rich was the passenger in the vehicle, while was looking on my phone I heard Brandi yell than, I looked up and thought I saw something yellow, sort of a flash of yellow. I closed my eyes than I saw her bleeding and the glass caved in. I had to grasp the wheel to pull over to the side of the road. Pedestrian #1: Name / DOB:Sebastian Guzman Vasquez /DOB: 05/15/1997 License Number / State:None Address:9304 Piney Branch Rd. Apt. 202 Silver Spring, MD 20903 Phone Number:(301) 835-3720 Injured Status:Fatality Impairment:Toxicology Report: Positive for alcohol - 0.23 BAC / Positive for Cocaine Statement:None Section VI. - Follow-up Investigation: Date:04/25/2023 See attached supplemental report completed by D/Sgt. Heath regarding positively identifying the Pedestrian as Sebastian Guzman Vasquez (H/M DOB: 05/15/1997). Section VII. - Analysis of Electronic Control Modules: The airbag control module (ACM) of the Honda Accord was not imaged. Section VIII. - Speed Analysis: No speed analysis was conducted. Section IX. - Crash Dynamics: The Honda Accord was traveling in lane 2 of the travel portion of the roadway. Guzman-Vasquez was in the path of the Honda Accord and was struck initially by the front drivers side of the vehicle in the area of the headlight causing Guzman-Vasquez to wrap over the hood and into the windshield. Based off of vehicle evidence and body matter and fluid present on scene, it appears Guzman-Vasquez head contacted the Honda Accord at the roof line of the windshield. Guzman-Vasquez was then thrown approximately 976 into lane 1 then continued to slide and tumble for another 11111 to his final rest on the left edge of the left shoulder, totaling 2089 of distance travelled from the estimated area of impact. Section X. - Attachments that were included in for this report: The following items were attached to this report: margin-left:8px">Written Statements (Form 076) Completed by Miller and Rich margin-left:8px">Maryland State Police Death Investigation Report (MSP 89B) margin-left:8px">Maryland State Police Request for Laboratory Examination Chain of Custody Log (MSP 67) (X3) margin-left:8px">Diagram completed by TFC C. Rafter #6500 margin-left:8px">ACRS margin-left:8px">MSP 62 Photo Log margin-left:8px">MSP Forensic Sciences Division (FSD) Crime Scene Report margin-left:8px">MSP FSD Task List and Field Notes Conclusion: The following conclusions are based on the totality of this investigation, including witness statements and the physical evidence accumulated. My analysis of these conclusions is based upon my training, knowledge, and experience in the field of collision reconstruction. The Honda Accord was traveling westbound on the Capital Beltway being operated by Brandi Michelle Miller, who was properly licensed. Guzman-Vasquez was the involved pedestrian. Guzman-Vasquez was walking as a pedestrian in the westbound lanes of the Capital Beltway, a controlled access highway, in lane 2. During my investigation there was no evidence of damage not related to the collision was observed. I find the fault for this collision rest solely on Guzman-Vasquez. The case will remain open pending the retrieval of the autopsy report. Once the autopsy report is received, a closing supplement will be authored. Trooper Ryan Stewart #7590 College Park Barrack Q 10100 Rhode Island Ave. College Park, MD 20740 (301) 345-3101

On 04/25/2023 I, Detective Sergeant Heath currently assigned to the College Park Barrack, was contacted by the investigative office of the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner (OCME) in Baltimore, MD regarding the unidentified deceased victim in this investigation. OCME investigators stated that the Prince Georges County Police Department (PGPD) had recently contacted them regarding a missing person investigation they were currently handling. PGPD indicated to OCME investigators they were currently attempting to locate the whereabouts of a Hispanic male, reported missing from Prince Georges County on 03/26/2023. While speaking to PGPD investigators from the OCME believed it possible their missing person may potentially be the unidentified deceased victim. Using law enforcement databases I was able to locate reports for the PGPD missing person investigation. On 04/25/2023 I made contact with PGPD Detective Machicote who was leading the missing person investigation. After obtaining details of his case, I determined it likely his missing person and the unidentified deceased victim were one in the same. Detective Machicote and I compared clothing and physical descriptors and photographs. Collectively we both agreed the deceased victim was likely his missing person. Detective Machicote was able to provide the name and birthdate for the subject as Sebsatian Guzman-Vasquez. I was able to obtain contact information for the missing person reporting party, identified as the victims brother, Miguel Guzman-Vasquez. With the assistance of Trooper J. Gonzales I was able to schedule an interview of M. Guzman-Vasquez. On 04/27/2023 at approximately 2300 hours M. Guzman-Vasquez responded to the College Park Barrack where Trooper Gonzales and I conducted a recorded interview. The interview was captured on Trooper Gonzales body-worn camera system. Through translation, Trooper Gonzales learned M. Guzman-Vasquez last spoke to S. Guzman-Vasquez on 03/25/2023 after they completed work for the day. On 03/26/2023 at approximately 0100 hours S. Guzman-Vasquez attempted to contact him by telephone, and that was the last attempted contact he had had with anyone. He further stated that family members attempted calling and locating S. Guzman-Vasquez through 03/27/2023 with no success. M. Guzman-Vasquez stated that on 03/25/2023 S. Guzman-Vasquez was dropped off with a friend at the 7-11 on Edgewood Road in College Park, MD. He was unable to provide a name of the friend, but stated that eventually the friend left the 7-11 in a taxi without S. Guzman-Vasquez. He further stated that throughout the evening S. Guzman-Vasquez had been consuming several alcoholic beverages. It was likely that after having been left by his friend. S. Guzman-Vasquez was attempting to walk to his wifes house on Piney Branch Road. During the interview M. Guzman-Vasquez was shown photographs taken at the collision scene to include clothing and the victim. He was able to positively identify the deceased as S. Guzman-Vasquez and formal death notification was made at that time. S. Guzman-Vasquezs cellular telephone, recovered from the collision scene, was turned over to M. Guzman-Vasquez and documented on Form 67. Following positive identification both Detective Machicote and the OCME were notified. The OCME advised they would be updating the identification status of the victim. On 05/02/2023 I was contacted by Dr. King of the OCME who conducted initial autopsy of S. Guzman-Vasquez. Dr. King stated although his report had not yet been finalized, preliminarily the death was ruled accidental. He also indicated that preliminary toxicology results showed the presence of cocaine in S. Guzman-Vasquezs body as well as an alcohol concentration of .23%. This concludes my portion of investigation. Case closed.

Detailed Crash Investigation Supplement (For review by the MSPCrash Team) Section I. Narrative On May 19, 2023 I received the autopsy report for the deceased in reference to this case, identified as Sebastian Guzman Vasquez (H/M 5/15/97) by next of kin, from the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner (OCME). During the review of the autopsy report it is indicated that Guzman sustained multiple injuries to include bone fractures, dislocations, lacerations and hemorrhaging. Guzman sustained substantial trauma focused on the left side of his body from the collision. Some of the noted injuries include multiple skull fractures/dislocation, C1/C2 fracture/dislocation, fractures/dislocations of multiple bones/joints in the left arm, and internal/organ injuries. It is noted in the report Guzman had been consuming alcoholic beverages and cocaine (a drug) prior to death. Toxicology results are as follows: Ethanol Urine 0.29% Vitreous 0.26% Benzoylecgonine (the major metabolite of cocaine) Blood Cavity: 0.099 mg/L The OCME states Guzman dies of multiple injuries sustained as a pedestrian involved in a motor vehicle crash and it manner of death is accident. Section II. - Attachments that were included in for this report: The following items were attached to this report: margin-left:8px">Office of the Chief Medical Examiner (OCME) Report. Conclusion: This case is closed due to the death of at-fault party. Trooper Ryan Stewart #7590 Golden Ring Barrack R 8908 Kelso Dr. Essex, MD 21221 (410) 780-2700
